  "prompt": "What is the main function of the brachiocephalic artery?",
  "response": "The **brachiocephalic artery**, also known as the **innominate artery**, is a major blood vessel that arises from the aortic arch. Its primary function is to supply oxygenated blood to the upper right part of the body. Specifically, it branches into two key arteries:\n\n1. **Right common carotid artery**: Supplies blood to the right side of the head and neck.\n2. **Right subclavian artery**: Supplies blood to the right arm and parts of the chest and shoulder.\n\nIn summary, the brachiocephalic artery plays a critical role in delivering oxygen-rich blood to the right side of the head, neck, and upper limb.",
